WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.540 --> 00:00:03.940
Welcome to Jeremy’s IT Lab.

00:00:03.940 --> 00:00:07.350
This is a free, complete course for the CCNA.

00:00:07.350 --> 00:00:11.270
If you like these videos, please subscribe
to follow along with the series.

00:00:11.270 --> 00:00:15.920
Also, please like and leave a comment, and
share the video to help spread this free series

00:00:15.920 --> 00:00:16.930
of videos.

00:00:16.930 --> 00:00:18.810
Thanks for your help.

00:00:18.810 --> 00:00:21.450
In this video we will look at REST APIs.

00:00:21.450 --> 00:00:26.419
APIs are used to allow programs to exchange
information with each other.

00:00:26.419 --> 00:00:30.480
They are important for network automation
because they allow our programs to easily

00:00:30.480 --> 00:00:34.230
interact with network devices and controllers.

00:00:34.230 --> 00:00:39.390
REST APIs specifically are commonly used for
the Northbound interface in SDN architecture.

00:00:39.390 --> 00:00:45.260
I’ve already briefly introduced REST APIs
and SDN, but in this video we’ll look at

00:00:45.260 --> 00:00:51.210
REST APIs in greater depth, and then in the
next we’ll do the same for SDN.

00:00:51.210 --> 00:00:56.900
This video will cover exam topic 6.5, which
states that you must be able to describe characteristics

00:00:56.900 --> 00:00:58.980
of REST-based APIs.

00:00:58.980 --> 00:01:04.440
So, as with all of the exam topics in this
section, Cisco doesn’t expect you to master

00:01:04.440 --> 00:01:09.050
the use of REST APIs, they just expect you
to have a foundational understanding.

00:01:09.050 --> 00:01:13.060
Here’s what we’ll cover in this video.

00:01:13.060 --> 00:01:15.620
First I’ll briefly review APIs.

00:01:15.620 --> 00:01:20.050
Then I’ll introduce CRUD operations and
HTTP.

00:01:20.050 --> 00:01:25.570
CRUD stands for Create, Read, Update, and
Delete, and it refers to the different actions

00:01:25.570 --> 00:01:28.510
we perform when using REST APIs.

00:01:28.510 --> 00:01:35.369
HTTP also uses CRUD operations, and REST APIs
often use HTTP as their communication protocol

00:01:35.369 --> 00:01:40.280
over the network, so it’s important to understand
HTTP.

00:01:40.280 --> 00:01:45.330
Then I’ll outline the characteristics of
REST APIs, and finally we’ll use Cisco DevNet

00:01:45.330 --> 00:01:50.460
to try out a couple basic REST API Calls,
and it’s free to use so you can follow along

00:01:50.460 --> 00:01:51.979
too.

00:01:51.979 --> 00:01:56.549
Make sure to watch until the end of the video
for a bonus practice question from Boson Software’s

00:01:56.549 --> 00:01:59.619
ExSim, the best practice exams for the CCNA.

00:01:59.619 --> 00:02:04.310
So, let’s quickly review what an API is.

00:02:04.310 --> 00:02:10.140
An API, application programming interface,
is a software interface that allows two applications

00:02:10.140 --> 00:02:12.609
to communicate with each other.

00:02:12.609 --> 00:02:17.489
They are essential not just for network automation,
but for all kinds of applications.

00:02:17.489 --> 00:02:21.791
If you want other applications to be able
to access data from your application, you

00:02:21.791 --> 00:02:24.940
should design an API that allows them to access
it.

00:02:24.940 --> 00:02:30.430
Here’s that basic diagram of SDN architecture
again, which we’ll cover in greater detail

00:02:30.430 --> 00:02:32.799
in the next video.

00:02:32.799 --> 00:02:38.909
In SDN architecture, APIs are used to communicate
between apps and the SDN controller via the

00:02:38.909 --> 00:02:42.799
northbound interface, and between the SDN
controller and the network devices via the

00:02:42.799 --> 00:02:45.239
southbound interface.

00:02:45.239 --> 00:02:50.200
The NBI typically uses REST APIs, the topic
of this video.

00:02:50.200 --> 00:02:54.829
Some other examples of APIs that can be used
to configure network devices via the southbound

00:02:54.829 --> 00:02:59.919
interface are NETCONF and RESTCONF, but we
won’t cover those in this video.

00:02:59.919 --> 00:03:04.760
You’ll have to learn more about those for
the CCNP and beyond, however.

00:03:04.760 --> 00:03:08.290
So, let’s take a look at CRUD.

00:03:08.290 --> 00:03:13.939
CRUD stands for Create, Read, Update, Delete,
and it refers to the operations we perform

00:03:13.939 --> 00:03:15.389
using REST APIs.

00:03:15.389 --> 00:03:20.719
But this CRUD framework isn’t just used
by REST APIs, and I’ll introduce it using

00:03:20.719 --> 00:03:24.010
HTTP in the next slide.

00:03:24.010 --> 00:03:28.400
First let’s look at the definition of each
of those operations.

00:03:28.400 --> 00:03:33.450
Create operations are used to create new variables
and set their initial values.

00:03:33.450 --> 00:03:41.279
For example, you could create a variable “ip_address”
and set the value to “10.1.1.1”.

00:03:41.279 --> 00:03:45.749
Read operations are used to retrieve the value
of a variable, for example you could then

00:03:45.749 --> 00:03:50.779
ask ‘What is the value of variable “ip_address”?

00:03:50.779 --> 00:03:55.099
Update operations are used to change the value
of a variable, for example you could change

00:03:55.099 --> 00:04:00.249
the value of the variable “ip_address”
to “10.2.3.4”.

00:04:00.249 --> 00:04:04.409
And finally delete operations are used to
delete variables, so you could delete the

00:04:04.409 --> 00:04:06.299
variable “ip_address”.

00:04:06.299 --> 00:04:10.989
So, those are the CRUD operations, now let’s
look at HTTP.

00:04:10.989 --> 00:04:16.780
First, why should I talk about HTTP, even
though this video is about REST?

00:04:16.780 --> 00:04:22.830
First, HTTP uses ‘verbs’ or ‘methods’
that map to these CRUD operations, and these

00:04:22.830 --> 00:04:27.910
CRUD operations match the actions we typically
want to perform with an application.

00:04:27.910 --> 00:04:33.200
When an HTTP client sends a request to an
HTTP server, it includes a verb indicating

00:04:33.200 --> 00:04:35.120
what the client wants to do.

00:04:35.120 --> 00:04:39.840
For example, if the client is trying to access
a web page on a server, it will use the GET

00:04:39.840 --> 00:04:44.250
verb to retrieve that web page, to get it,
from the server.

00:04:44.250 --> 00:04:49.280
And for this reason, among others, REST APIs
typically use HTTP as their application-layer

00:04:49.280 --> 00:04:52.040
protocol to communicate over the network.

00:04:52.040 --> 00:04:57.370
So, let’s compare these CRUD operations
to HTTP verbs.

00:04:57.370 --> 00:04:59.260
Here is a simple chart.

00:04:59.260 --> 00:05:04.040
The HTTP verb POST is used to create a new
variable.

00:05:04.040 --> 00:05:07.730
The equivalent of a read operation is GET.

00:05:07.730 --> 00:05:12.750
There are two main options for the update
operation, PUT and PATCH, and the verb for

00:05:12.750 --> 00:05:15.970
the delete operation is simply DELETE.

00:05:15.970 --> 00:05:19.680
You don’t have to know the exact details
of these verbs, but definitely know which

00:05:19.680 --> 00:05:22.590
ones are used for which CRUD operation.

00:05:22.590 --> 00:05:25.560
The flashcards will help with remembering
them.

00:05:25.560 --> 00:05:29.970
There are other HTTP verbs too, and you can
see them in this guide from Mozilla if you

00:05:29.970 --> 00:05:31.780
want to learn more.

00:05:31.780 --> 00:05:35.900
Let’s look more at how those verbs are used.

00:05:35.900 --> 00:05:42.330
When an HTTP client, or a REST client using
HTTP, sends a request to a server, it includes

00:05:42.330 --> 00:05:48.900
some information such as an HTTP verb, which
I just introduced and a URI, uniform resource

00:05:48.900 --> 00:05:52.260
identifier, indicating the resource it is
trying to access.

00:05:52.260 --> 00:06:00.050
So, here we have a server storing data as
variables, with a URI for each resource.

00:06:00.050 --> 00:06:06.010
The client sends a GET message, for example,
trying to retrieve the resource with URI A.

00:06:06.010 --> 00:06:09.780
The server would then send a response, but
I’ll get into the details of the response

00:06:09.780 --> 00:06:10.800
soon.

00:06:10.800 --> 00:06:17.300
Here’s an example of a URI, and I’ll use
this URI later when demonstrating a REST API

00:06:17.300 --> 00:06:19.900
call on Cisco DevNet.

00:06:19.900 --> 00:06:22.120
Note the three main sections.

00:06:22.120 --> 00:06:25.090
First is the scheme, which is basically the
protocol.

00:06:25.090 --> 00:06:32.600
In this case HTTP, or more specifically HTTPS,
HTTP Secure, is the protocol.

00:06:32.600 --> 00:06:34.150
Then there is the authority.

00:06:34.150 --> 00:06:38.970
This is basically the address, or hostname,
you are sending the request to.

00:06:38.970 --> 00:06:43.070
After that is the path, this indicates the
resource you want to access.

00:06:43.070 --> 00:06:49.530
Now, the Verb and URI are just part of the
HTTP request, let’s look at some more of

00:06:49.530 --> 00:06:50.530
an HTTP request.

00:06:50.530 --> 00:06:59.280
The HTTP request can include additional headers
which pass additional information to the server.

00:06:59.280 --> 00:07:02.080
There is a great list at this page here from
Mozilla.

00:07:02.080 --> 00:07:06.620
Here’s an example of an HTTP request message.

00:07:06.620 --> 00:07:13.080
On the outside there is an IP header and a
TCP header, then the HTTP verb and URI, followed

00:07:13.080 --> 00:07:16.090
by some additional headers and data.

00:07:16.090 --> 00:07:20.340
An example header would be the Accept header,
which informs the server about the type or

00:07:20.340 --> 00:07:24.360
types of data that can be sent back to the
client.

00:07:24.360 --> 00:07:29.050
The client might say I accept JSON data or
XML data, for example.

00:07:29.050 --> 00:07:34.460
There’s another list of standard HTTP headers
here on Wikipedia, and there are examples

00:07:34.460 --> 00:07:38.600
for each header so you can see what kind of
information is included.

00:07:38.600 --> 00:07:43.190
Now, before I continue I want to clarify once
more why I’m spending so much time talking

00:07:43.190 --> 00:07:47.639
about HTTP in a video that’s supposed to
be about REST APIs.

00:07:47.639 --> 00:07:54.000
It’s because when a REST client makes an
API call, a request to a REST server, it will

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:56.460
send an HTTP request like the one above.

00:07:56.460 --> 00:08:01.020
So, you have to understand some basics about
HTTP.

00:08:01.020 --> 00:08:06.210
Note that REST APIs don’t actually HAVE
to use HTTP for communication, although HTTP

00:08:06.210 --> 00:08:08.400
is the most common choice.

00:08:08.400 --> 00:08:13.540
For the purpose of the CCNA you can assume
that REST APIs use HTTP, but just keep in

00:08:13.540 --> 00:08:19.020
mind that HTTP is a specific communication
protocol, and REST is a framework for building

00:08:19.020 --> 00:08:20.020
APIs.

00:08:20.020 --> 00:08:23.810
They aren’t the same thing, and they aren’t
always used together.

00:08:23.810 --> 00:08:30.290
Now, after the client’s HTTP request the
server has to send a response.

00:08:30.290 --> 00:08:33.940
Let’s look a bit at what is in that response.

00:08:33.940 --> 00:08:38.559
The server’s response will include a status
code indicating if the request succeeded or

00:08:38.559 --> 00:08:41.599
failed, as well as other details.

00:08:41.599 --> 00:08:46.290
You might not know it, but I’m sure you’ve
seen at least one of these codes before.

00:08:46.290 --> 00:08:50.819
The first digit indicates the class, the type,
of the response.

00:08:50.819 --> 00:08:52.959
Here are the different classes.

00:08:52.959 --> 00:08:57.970
If the response code begins with a 1, it is
an informational response.

00:08:57.970 --> 00:09:02.200
This indicates that the server received the
request, but the exact meaning beyond that

00:09:02.200 --> 00:09:05.240
depends on the remaining two digits of the
response code.

00:09:05.240 --> 00:09:09.259
We’ll look at an example in the next slide.

00:09:09.259 --> 00:09:13.889
If the response code begins with a 2, the
class is ‘successful’.

00:09:13.889 --> 00:09:18.519
This means the request was successfully received,
understood, and accepted.

00:09:18.519 --> 00:09:22.529
This is usually the class of response you
want from the server.

00:09:22.529 --> 00:09:26.360
If the response code begins with a 3 the class
is redirection.

00:09:26.360 --> 00:09:32.199
It means that further action is required to
be taken in order to complete the request.

00:09:32.199 --> 00:09:37.199
For example, if the URI of the resource has
been changed, this response can tell the client

00:09:37.199 --> 00:09:41.120
to request the new URI to get the resource.

00:09:41.120 --> 00:09:45.850
If the response code begins with a 4, the
response class is client error.

00:09:45.850 --> 00:09:50.290
This means there was some error in the request
and it can’t be fulfilled, such as requesting

00:09:50.290 --> 00:09:52.779
a resource that doesn’t exist.

00:09:52.779 --> 00:09:54.620
Let me show an example of that.

00:09:54.620 --> 00:09:59.930
The client sends a GET request for the resource
at URI G, however that doesn’t exist on

00:09:59.930 --> 00:10:00.930
the server.

00:10:00.930 --> 00:10:07.480
So, it sends a response with response code
404, indicating the resource was not found.

00:10:07.480 --> 00:10:12.269
I think many of you will recognize the 404
code, you’ve probably seen it on the Internet

00:10:12.269 --> 00:10:13.819
before.

00:10:13.819 --> 00:10:19.740
For example, I tried to access google.com/jeremysitlab,
and I got an error message.

00:10:19.740 --> 00:10:23.720
Notice the response code, 404, indicating
that the resource was not found.

00:10:23.720 --> 00:10:30.379
I got this error message because google.com/jeremysitlab
doesn’t exist, at least not until Google

00:10:30.379 --> 00:10:33.760
acquires my company for the low price of a
billion dollars.

00:10:33.760 --> 00:10:37.240
If anyone from Google’s watching, I’m
waiting for your offer.

00:10:37.240 --> 00:10:40.930
Anyway, there is one more class of response.

00:10:40.930 --> 00:10:45.529
If the response code begins with a 5 the class
is server error.

00:10:45.529 --> 00:10:49.839
This means that the request was valid, but
the server was unable to fulfill it for some

00:10:49.839 --> 00:10:50.839
reason.

00:10:50.839 --> 00:10:57.410
For example, perhaps the server doesn’t
support the HTTP version of the request.

00:10:57.410 --> 00:11:00.620
Here are some examples of each HTTP Response
class.

00:11:00.620 --> 00:11:03.850
I’ll just give one or two examples for each.

00:11:03.850 --> 00:11:09.139
For the informational class, you might see
code 102, which means processing.

00:11:09.139 --> 00:11:13.050
This indicates that the server has received
the request and is processing it, but the

00:11:13.050 --> 00:11:15.899
response is not yet available.

00:11:15.899 --> 00:11:20.119
For the successful class you might see code
200, meaning OK.

00:11:20.119 --> 00:11:22.149
This indicates that the request succeeded.

00:11:22.149 --> 00:11:27.809
If this is in response to a GET request, for
example, the code 200 in the header will indicate

00:11:27.809 --> 00:11:33.819
it was successful, and in the message body
the requested resource is sent.

00:11:33.819 --> 00:11:39.260
Another example is 201, created, which indicates
that the request succeeded and a new resource

00:11:39.260 --> 00:11:43.040
was created, for example in response to a
POST request.

00:11:43.040 --> 00:11:48.029
Remember, POST is equivalent to the CRUD Create
operation.

00:11:48.029 --> 00:11:53.519
In the redirection class, 301, moved permanently,
indicates that the requested resource has

00:11:53.519 --> 00:11:58.470
been moved, and the server indicates its new
location to the client.

00:11:58.470 --> 00:12:02.319
In the client error class we have 403, unauthorized.

00:12:02.319 --> 00:12:06.339
This means that the client must authenticate
to get a response.

00:12:06.339 --> 00:12:11.839
Note that when talking about AAA in the security
section of the course I told you about authentication

00:12:11.839 --> 00:12:13.509
and authorization.

00:12:13.509 --> 00:12:15.160
They are different things.

00:12:15.160 --> 00:12:20.720
The official name for code 403 is unauthorized,
but maybe a better name would be unauthenticated,

00:12:20.720 --> 00:12:23.889
because it indicates that the client needs
to authenticate.

00:12:23.889 --> 00:12:29.670
Another example is 404, indicating that the
requested resource was not found.

00:12:29.670 --> 00:12:35.860
Finally, an example of the server error class
is 500 internal server error, indicating that

00:12:35.860 --> 00:12:40.300
the server encountered something unexpected
that it doesn’t know how to handle.

00:12:40.300 --> 00:12:45.189
These are just a few examples, but there are
many more HTTP response codes.

00:12:45.189 --> 00:12:50.149
If you’re curious about the others, check
out this page, once again from Mozilla.

00:12:50.149 --> 00:12:54.559
You can also check out this page for a summary
of which Response codes you might see in response

00:12:54.559 --> 00:12:56.759
to each HTTP verb.

00:12:56.759 --> 00:13:00.820
Okay, that’s enough about HTTP.

00:13:00.820 --> 00:13:06.119
Let’s finally take a look at some characteristics
of REST APIs.

00:13:06.119 --> 00:13:09.619
REST stands for representational state transfer.

00:13:09.619 --> 00:13:14.220
And REST APIs are also known as REST-based
APIs or RESTful APIs.

00:13:14.220 --> 00:13:17.829
I usually just call them REST APIs.

00:13:17.829 --> 00:13:21.439
Note that, as I’ve said before, REST isn’t
a specific API.

00:13:21.439 --> 00:13:25.750
Rather, it describes a set of rules about
how the API should work.

00:13:25.750 --> 00:13:28.720
It’s a framework for APIs.

00:13:28.720 --> 00:13:35.290
The six constraints, or rules, of RESTful
architecture are a uniform interface, client-server

00:13:35.290 --> 00:13:42.129
architecture, stateless operations, cacheable
(or non-cacheable) functions, a layered system,

00:13:42.129 --> 00:13:45.199
and optionally something called code-on-demand.

00:13:45.199 --> 00:13:49.709
If you’re curious to know more details about
all of these requirements check out this link,

00:13:49.709 --> 00:13:53.990
but now I will explain just a few of them
that I think you should know for the CCNA.

00:13:53.990 --> 00:13:57.660
The first is client-server.

00:13:57.660 --> 00:14:01.990
REST APIs use a client-server architecture,
like HTTP.

00:14:01.990 --> 00:14:08.060
The client uses API calls, basically that
means HTTP requests, to access resources on

00:14:08.060 --> 00:14:11.550
the server, such as in the example below.

00:14:11.550 --> 00:14:15.639
The separation between the client and server
means that they can both change and evolve

00:14:15.639 --> 00:14:19.970
independently of each other, they aren’t
dependent on one another.

00:14:19.970 --> 00:14:24.699
And when the client application changes or
the server application changes, the interface

00:14:24.699 --> 00:14:27.790
between them must not break, it should continue
to function.

00:14:27.790 --> 00:14:32.660
I think you’re fairly familiar with client-server
architecture already, it’s used in various

00:14:32.660 --> 00:14:35.889
aspects of networking.

00:14:35.889 --> 00:14:40.350
The next characteristic I want to cover is
that REST API exchanges are stateless.

00:14:40.350 --> 00:14:45.720
I haven’t mentioned this term yet in the
course, but it’s an important one.

00:14:45.720 --> 00:14:50.629
Statelessness means that each API exchange
is a separate event, independent of all past

00:14:50.629 --> 00:14:52.980
exchanges between the client and server.

00:14:52.980 --> 00:14:57.790
So, the server does not store information
about previous requests to determine how it

00:14:57.790 --> 00:15:00.250
should respond to new requests.

00:15:00.250 --> 00:15:03.600
Each new request is a totally separate event.

00:15:03.600 --> 00:15:07.540
And if authentication is required, this means
that the client has to authenticate with the

00:15:07.540 --> 00:15:10.730
server for each request it makes.

00:15:10.730 --> 00:15:15.189
Although I haven’t used the term stateless,
or stateful, in the course yet, I have introduced

00:15:15.189 --> 00:15:18.059
some stateful and stateless protocols.

00:15:18.059 --> 00:15:21.160
For example, TCP is stateful.

00:15:21.160 --> 00:15:25.970
It establishes connections and uses sequence
and acknowledgment numbers to keep track of

00:15:25.970 --> 00:15:27.490
the exchanges between hosts.

00:15:27.490 --> 00:15:30.459
UDP, on the other hand, is stateless.

00:15:30.459 --> 00:15:35.879
No connection is set up and neither host keeps
track of any sequence or acknowledgment numbers.

00:15:35.879 --> 00:15:40.980
The data is simply sent from host A to host
B, UDP doesn’t keep track of the state of

00:15:40.980 --> 00:15:42.189
the exchange.

00:15:42.189 --> 00:15:45.790
Now, I want to make a clarification.

00:15:45.790 --> 00:15:52.730
Although REST APIs use HTTP, which uses TCP
as its Layer 4 protocol, HTTP and REST APIs

00:15:52.730 --> 00:15:55.389
themselves aren’t stateful.

00:15:55.389 --> 00:15:59.819
Keep in mind that the functions of the layers
of the OSI model are separate.

00:15:59.819 --> 00:16:04.160
Just because a stateful Layer 4 protocol is
used doesn’t mean that the application layer

00:16:04.160 --> 00:16:06.920
protocol must also be stateful.

00:16:06.920 --> 00:16:13.509
The last rule of REST APIs that I’ll mention
is the cacheable OR non-cacheable requirement.

00:16:13.509 --> 00:16:15.389
Let me explain.

00:16:15.389 --> 00:16:21.579
REST APIs must support caching of data, basically
that means storing data for future use.

00:16:21.579 --> 00:16:25.069
You might have heard this term before in reference
to web browsing.

00:16:25.069 --> 00:16:29.230
For example, your computer might cache many
elements of a web page so that it doesn’t

00:16:29.230 --> 00:16:32.889
have to retrieve the entire page every time
you visit it.

00:16:32.889 --> 00:16:37.119
This improves performance for the client and
reduces the load on the server.

00:16:37.119 --> 00:16:43.240
So, caching must be supported, but that doesn’t
mean that every resource has to be cacheable.

00:16:43.240 --> 00:16:48.170
Not all resources have to be cacheable, but
cacheable resources must be declared as cacheable

00:16:48.170 --> 00:16:55.010
when the server sends them to the client,
so the client will cache them for future use.

00:16:55.010 --> 00:16:59.279
As I said before, if you’re curious about
the other aspects of REST APIs you can check

00:16:59.279 --> 00:17:04.130
this link for restfulapi.net, but those three
are the key ones you should understand for

00:17:04.130 --> 00:17:05.459
now.

00:17:05.459 --> 00:17:08.540
And I’m repeating myself, but let me say
this again.

00:17:08.540 --> 00:17:13.490
For applications to communicate over a network,
networking protocols must be used to facilitate

00:17:13.490 --> 00:17:15.720
those communications.

00:17:15.720 --> 00:17:21.890
And for REST APIs, HTTP is the most common
choice, or more often HTTPS, its encrypted

00:17:21.890 --> 00:17:23.360
version is used.

00:17:23.360 --> 00:17:26.300
That’s all we’ll cover for REST.

00:17:26.300 --> 00:17:33.360
For the CCNA, Make sure you know the CRUD
actions, HTTP client request verbs, HTTP server

00:17:33.360 --> 00:17:38.740
response codes, and the basic characteristics
of REST APIs that we covered in this video.

00:17:38.740 --> 00:17:43.370
Now let’s move on to try some simple REST
API calls using free resources provided by

00:17:43.370 --> 00:17:45.450
Cisco DevNet.

00:17:45.450 --> 00:17:48.140
So, what is Cisco DevNet?

00:17:48.140 --> 00:17:51.520
I’ll let them describe it themselves.

00:17:51.520 --> 00:17:56.280
Cisco DevNet is Cisco’s developer program
to help developers and IT professionals who

00:17:56.280 --> 00:18:02.180
want to write applications and develop integrations
with Cisco products, platforms, and APIs.

00:18:02.180 --> 00:18:05.440
There’s the magic word, API.

00:18:05.440 --> 00:18:11.830
Basically, DevNet offers lots of free resources
such as courses, tutorials, labs, sandboxes,

00:18:11.830 --> 00:18:16.390
documentation, etc. to learn about automation
and develop your skills.

00:18:16.390 --> 00:18:19.870
It really is a great resource and it keeps
getting better.

00:18:19.870 --> 00:18:23.830
Note that there is also a DevNet certification
track that you can pursue if you’re interested

00:18:23.830 --> 00:18:25.050
in network automation.

00:18:25.050 --> 00:18:30.760
If that’s the case for you, perhaps consider
the DevNet associate cert after you get your

00:18:30.760 --> 00:18:31.850
CCNA.

00:18:31.850 --> 00:18:38.490
Today we will use their Cisco DNA Center Sandbox
to send a REST API call using Postman.

00:18:38.490 --> 00:18:43.700
DNA Center is one of Cisco’s SDN controllers,
and we’ll cover it in the next video when

00:18:43.700 --> 00:18:47.000
we go more in depth regarding SDN.

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:51.980
DevNet has various always-on sandboxes, which
are devices you are free to access at any

00:18:51.980 --> 00:18:55.630
time and look around to get familiar with
them.

00:18:55.630 --> 00:18:59.730
In this case we’ll use their always-on DNA
Center sandbox.

00:18:59.730 --> 00:19:04.360
And Postman, which we’ll use to send the
API calls, is a platform for building and

00:19:04.360 --> 00:19:05.360
using APIs.

00:19:05.360 --> 00:19:07.630
It’s also a great learning tool.

00:19:07.630 --> 00:19:14.170
So, to start I want you to make an account
on DevNet, developer.cisco.com, and also make

00:19:14.170 --> 00:19:18.360
an account on postman.com and download the
desktop app.

00:19:18.360 --> 00:19:23.530
You can use it directly in your browser too,
but I like to use the desktop app.

00:19:23.530 --> 00:19:28.150
For this demonstration we will simply follow
this short tutorial on DevNet.

00:19:28.150 --> 00:19:33.180
Go to this link or just do a google search
for ‘devnet dna center getting started’,

00:19:33.180 --> 00:19:35.490
it should be the top result.

00:19:35.490 --> 00:19:39.810
Note that you don’t have to follow along,
you can just watch me do it, but I do recommend

00:19:39.810 --> 00:19:42.000
that you try it out yourself.

00:19:42.000 --> 00:19:45.710
But even if you’re just following what I’m
doing, make sure you read the tutorial on

00:19:45.710 --> 00:19:49.400
DevNet too because it will explain the reason
for each of the steps.

00:19:49.400 --> 00:19:51.200
I’ll just show you them.

00:19:51.200 --> 00:19:56.950
So, I’ve installed the Postman desktop app
and opened it.

00:19:56.950 --> 00:20:01.820
From the home screen, click on workspaces
and and select My Workspace.

00:20:01.820 --> 00:20:09.100
If you don’t have a workspace you can create
one by clicking where it says ‘create workspace’.

00:20:09.100 --> 00:20:10.930
Now I’m in my workspace.

00:20:10.930 --> 00:20:14.250
Next you should click New here.

00:20:14.250 --> 00:20:17.940
That will open this window, where you can
select what you want to create.

00:20:17.940 --> 00:20:25.810
For example, you can create a new API, documentation
for an API, a mock server to test APIs, etc.

00:20:25.810 --> 00:20:30.930
In this case, we want to create an HTTP request
which we will send to DevNet’s DNA center

00:20:30.930 --> 00:20:33.680
server.

00:20:33.680 --> 00:20:38.480
After clicking on HTTP request, we can now
specify what kind of HTTP request we want

00:20:38.480 --> 00:20:42.040
to send to DNA center’s REST API.

00:20:42.040 --> 00:20:47.660
As explained in the DevNet tutorial, first
we have to generate an authorization token

00:20:47.660 --> 00:20:50.880
which we will use for our second HTTP request.

00:20:50.880 --> 00:20:56.540
First, set the HTTP verb to POST, it is GET
by default.

00:20:56.540 --> 00:20:59.350
Then we have to specify the URL.

00:20:59.350 --> 00:21:05.010
Just a quick note, the DevNet tutorial uses
the term URL, Uniform Resource Locator, but

00:21:05.010 --> 00:21:10.000
I used the term URI, Uniform Resource Identifier,
earlier in the video.

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:14.420
Basically, a URL is just a type of URI.

00:21:14.420 --> 00:21:18.050
You can google ‘URI vs URL’ for more info.

00:21:18.050 --> 00:21:24.920
So, if we send a POST request to this URL,
an authorization token will be generated.

00:21:24.920 --> 00:21:29.170
However we have to specify a username and
password for that to happen.

00:21:29.170 --> 00:21:35.540
To do that, click on authorization here, and
then select Basic Auth.

00:21:35.540 --> 00:21:39.810
That will open this menu, where you should
enter these credentials.

00:21:39.810 --> 00:21:45.620
Username devnetuser, password Cisco123! with
a capital C and an exclamation point at the

00:21:45.620 --> 00:21:46.620
end.

00:21:46.620 --> 00:21:53.920
Okay, the POST is ready so now we can click
send to send the POST request to DNA center’s

00:21:53.920 --> 00:21:55.030
API.

00:21:55.030 --> 00:22:00.010
If the POST is successful you will get a response
with code 200, OK.

00:22:00.010 --> 00:22:05.380
The body of the response message will include
your authorization token in JSON key-value

00:22:05.380 --> 00:22:06.380
format.

00:22:06.380 --> 00:22:08.080
Make sure to copy the value of the token.

00:22:08.080 --> 00:22:14.720
You don’t have to copy the quotation marks
around the string, just the part I’ve highlighted.

00:22:14.720 --> 00:22:20.220
Okay, now we’re ready to send the second
API call, which will retrieve a device inventory

00:22:20.220 --> 00:22:22.590
from the DNA center controller.

00:22:22.590 --> 00:22:26.620
First, change the HTTP verb to GET.

00:22:26.620 --> 00:22:31.760
We will also send this request to a different
URL, as written in the tutorial.

00:22:31.760 --> 00:22:37.280
And the next step is to add an additional
HTTP header with our authentication token.

00:22:37.280 --> 00:22:43.250
To do that, click on ‘headers’ here, enter
‘X-Auth-Token’ for the key, and in the

00:22:43.250 --> 00:22:48.310
value field paste the authorization key you
got from DNA center with the previous API

00:22:48.310 --> 00:22:49.310
call.

00:22:49.310 --> 00:22:57.170
Okay, now we’re ready for the second API
call, click on send to send the GET request.

00:22:57.170 --> 00:23:03.130
If the GET is successful, you will once again
get a response with a 200 OK code.

00:23:03.130 --> 00:23:08.220
And in the body we get the requested information,
JSON-formatted data listing the inventory

00:23:08.220 --> 00:23:12.030
of devices managed by the DNA center controller.

00:23:12.030 --> 00:23:17.880
The output here is quite long, but let me
show output for one of the devices.

00:23:17.880 --> 00:23:19.160
Here is that output.

00:23:19.160 --> 00:23:22.810
You should be familiar with the format, as
I mentioned it’s JSON.

00:23:22.810 --> 00:23:27.710
So, by looking at this output we can learn
about this device that is managed by the DNA

00:23:27.710 --> 00:23:29.820
center controller.

00:23:29.820 --> 00:23:34.150
For example, the device family is listed as
switches or hubs.

00:23:34.150 --> 00:23:38.610
Since hubs aren’t really used anymore, it’s
safe to say that this is a switch.

00:23:38.610 --> 00:23:42.010
The role is access, so it’s an access layer
switch.

00:23:42.010 --> 00:23:44.890
The hostname is leaf1.abc.com.

00:23:44.890 --> 00:23:50.250
Leaf1, perhaps that means this is a leaf switch
in a spine-leaf architecture.

00:23:50.250 --> 00:23:55.560
Here’s the platform ID, C9300-24U.

00:23:55.560 --> 00:23:58.460
This is the device model, Catalyst 9300.

00:23:58.460 --> 00:24:02.100
Here’s a picture of a C9300, by the way.

00:24:02.100 --> 00:24:07.040
We can also get info like the uptime, how
much time has passed since the device booted

00:24:07.040 --> 00:24:08.040
up.

00:24:08.040 --> 00:24:14.450
So, that was a quick look at some basic REST
API calls to Cisco DNA Center using Postman.

00:24:14.450 --> 00:24:20.020
We retrieved data in a machine-readable format,
JSON, so we can write applications that gather

00:24:20.020 --> 00:24:25.190
data like this, interact with it, tell DNA
center to change it, etc.

00:24:25.190 --> 00:24:28.990
We’ve barely scratched the surface, but
I hope you’re starting to see the utility

00:24:28.990 --> 00:24:30.940
of APIs.

00:24:30.940 --> 00:24:34.640
Here’s what we covered in this video.

00:24:34.640 --> 00:24:39.530
We briefly reviewed what an API is, and then
looked at CRUD operations and their equivalent

00:24:39.530 --> 00:24:41.980
HTTP verbs.

00:24:41.980 --> 00:24:46.690
Then we looked at the basic characteristics
of REST APIs, and finally tried a few REST

00:24:46.690 --> 00:24:51.530
API Calls to DNA Center using a Cisco DevNet
tutorial.

00:24:51.530 --> 00:24:57.150
As I mentioned earlier, make sure you know
the CRUD actions, HTTP client request verbs,

00:24:57.150 --> 00:25:02.400
HTTP server response codes, and the basic
characteristics of REST APIs that I covered

00:25:02.400 --> 00:25:03.490
in this video.

00:25:03.490 --> 00:25:09.150
I also gave various links to different resources
throughout the video that I recommend reading,

00:25:09.150 --> 00:25:12.160
although they will go in much more depth than
is required.

00:25:12.160 --> 00:25:15.440
But check them out if you want a greater understanding.

00:25:15.440 --> 00:25:19.480
And make sure to watch until the end of the
quiz for a bonus practice question from Boson

00:25:19.480 --> 00:25:23.270
Software’s ExSim, the best practice exams
for the CCNA.

00:25:23.270 --> 00:25:28.600
Okay, let’s go to quiz question 1.

00:25:28.600 --> 00:25:33.730
What HTTP response code would you expect to
receive if you tried to GET a resource that

00:25:33.730 --> 00:25:35.650
doesn’t exist on the server?

00:25:35.650 --> 00:25:40.320
Pause the video now to select the best answer.

00:25:40.320 --> 00:25:45.580
Okay, the answer is B, 404.

00:25:45.580 --> 00:25:47.740
This code means Not Found.

00:25:47.740 --> 00:25:52.450
If the requested resource does not exist on
the server, you can expect this response code.

00:25:52.450 --> 00:25:56.980
Okay, let’s go to question 2.

00:25:56.980 --> 00:26:00.700
Which of the following is NOT a constraint
of RESTful architecture?

00:26:00.700 --> 00:26:05.610
Pause the video now to select the best answer.

00:26:05.610 --> 00:26:11.440
Okay, the answer is C, stateful.

00:26:11.440 --> 00:26:16.740
REST APIs are stateless, meaning that each
individual client request is a unique event,

00:26:16.740 --> 00:26:19.550
not dependent on any previous requests.

00:26:19.550 --> 00:26:24.200
In addition to these five constraints, there
is an optional one called ‘code on demand’,

00:26:24.200 --> 00:26:28.910
which basically extends client functionality
by allowing them to download and execute code

00:26:28.910 --> 00:26:30.030
from servers.

00:26:30.030 --> 00:26:34.510
Okay, let’s go to question 3.

00:26:34.510 --> 00:26:39.770
Which category of HTTP response would you
expect in response to a successful request?

00:26:39.770 --> 00:26:44.860
Pause the video now to select the best answer.

00:26:44.860 --> 00:26:52.350
Okay, the answer is B, you should expect a
response code beginning with 2.

00:26:52.350 --> 00:26:59.070
This indicates a successful request, for example
with the 200 OK response code or the 201 Created

00:26:59.070 --> 00:27:00.120
response code.

00:27:00.120 --> 00:27:03.910
Okay, let’s go to question 4.

00:27:03.910 --> 00:27:10.060
HTTP verbs PUT and PATCH are equivalent to
what CRUD operation?

00:27:10.060 --> 00:27:14.640
Pause the video now to select the best answer.

00:27:14.640 --> 00:27:21.140
Okay, the answer is C, U, which stands for
update.

00:27:21.140 --> 00:27:25.790
Note that you might also see PUT categorized
as a Create action, because it can be used

00:27:25.790 --> 00:27:30.310
to create new variables, but usually it’s
used as an Update function.

00:27:30.310 --> 00:27:33.720
Okay, let’s go to question 5.

00:27:33.720 --> 00:27:39.410
Which of the following would you expect to
find as the scheme of a URI?

00:27:39.410 --> 00:27:43.720
Pause the video now to select the best answer.

00:27:43.720 --> 00:27:49.300
Okay, the answer is A, HTTPS.

00:27:49.300 --> 00:27:55.350
The scheme of a URI identifies the protocol
you are using, typically HTTP or HTTPS for

00:27:55.350 --> 00:27:57.640
web services and REST APIs.

00:27:57.640 --> 00:28:00.160
Okay, that’s all for the quiz.

00:28:00.160 --> 00:28:06.300
Now let’s take a look at a bonus question
in Boson Software’s ExSim for CCNA.

